        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>The Woman&#39;s Branch<lb/>
                of the <lb/>
                Pennsylvania Society<lb/>
                for the<lb/>
                Prevention of Cruelty to animals<lb/>
                No. 1002 Walnut Street&#44;<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44; January 8<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#44; 1886<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Rev Mr. Morais&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>A complaint has been made<lb/> to me of a number of the butchers employed<lb/> by your Board to kill the cattle in differ&#45;<lb/>ent places throughout the city according<lb/> to the Israelitish fashion. I have it<lb/> from the best authority that you have sev&#45;<lb/>eral men who do not know their business&#44;<lb/> and who instead of killing the cattle at<lb/> once&#44; or cutting their throats at once&#44;<lb/> saw and work at them in a most cruel<lb/> manner and one very distressing to behold.<lb/> The well known English veterinary sur&#45;<lb/>geon Mr. Gadden watched the killing<lb/> of a steer by one of these men&#44; and said<lb/> that instead of depriving the animal of<lb/> consciousness almost immediately as<lb/> he should have done&#44; that the poor creature<lb/> was in suffering for some time. The two<lb/> brothers named Michael are men who<lb/> do know their business&#44; and who make<lb/> the operation of killing as short as possible<lb/> Can you not&#44; my dear Sir&#44; give this mat&#45;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/> 
            <p>ter your attention&#44; and see that all the men<lb/> employed by your Board or Association<lb/> are as well instructed and a&#91;s&#93; skilled as<lb/> these Michael brothers. Our agent was<lb/> obliged to threaten one of these men who<lb/> performed the work in such a bungling<lb/> manner the <sic>the</sic> other day&#44; with arrest.<lb/>  We should prefer greatly that you would<lb/> take the matter in hand&#44; and that we<lb/> should not be obliged to proceed to such<lb/> extreme measures. Hoping that you<lb/> may be able to effect a change&#44; I remain<lb/></p>
            <p>yours very sincerely<lb/>
                Caroline Earle White<lb/>
                Pres. of  &#34;Women&#39;s Branch&#34;<lb/>
                of Penn. S.P.C.A.<lb/>
                2312 Delancey Place<lb/></p>
                
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Penna. S.P.C.A.<lb/>
                Rev. Mr. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> st. below Green&#44;<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44;<lb/></p>
